Plover JS/TS dictionary in strict, machine-parsable form. Parsed by src/parse.ts to emit stroking-based code templates. Each entry is a stroke (the shorthand on the fence) paired with a template (between fences); templates use operators like `%0` (landing point), `%d` (iteration index or total count in repeats), `%t` (type slot, filled by appended type stroke), and `%[sep|body%]` (repeat with joiner). Directives `@count`, `@arity`, `@multiline`, `@type`, `@literal`, `@fuse`, `@noarg` attach to entries above them.

The file is split into sections: functions (with `@fuse` merging return type into the shape stroke), params, if/else/ternary/loops, try/catch, switch, declarations, console/throw, classes, destructuring, array/string/Math methods (all keyed off the `STKWR*PLT` prefix + method selector), type emitters (where `%t` is a placeholder filled by secondary strokes, marked `@type` and `@arity N` for generics), and data structures (Stack, Queue, LinkedList, BST, Graph, Trie, etc.—all emitted whole via `@literal`).

Type slots (`%t`) are terminal when appended: `STKWR-T/TPH` → `number`; `STKWR-T/PR/STR` → `Promise<string>`. Generic types (`@arity > 0`) stay non-terminal until N type args are supplied. The `@fuse` directive on function templates causes the trailing type stroke to fold into the shape, so `STKWR-PBGS/-FLT` emits a number function directly. All repeat syntax (`%d` inside `%[...%]`) treats `%d` as the iteration index, and `%(EXPR)` allows computed landing points linear in `d`. Escapes `\n`, `\t`, `\{`, `\}`, `\%`, `\|`, `\\`, `` \` `` are literal; `%b` toggles as a one-liner flag across all occurrences in a translation together.